# 🚀 HackerRank – From Zero to Hero (Beginner → Advanced)

A complete, step-by-step guide to go from "I don't know coding" to solving hard problems confidently on HackerRank — and getting interview-ready.

**Goal**:  
Build strong problem-solving skills + get good at coding interviews (FAANG, startups, product companies, etc.)

**Time estimate** (serious daily practice):  
- Beginner → Intermediate: 3–6 months  
- Intermediate → Advanced: 6–12 months (depends on consistency)

## Who is this guide for?

- Never coded before  
- Know basics but stuck on easy problems  
- Want to crack coding interviews  
- Preparing for college placements / off-campus jobs  
- Self-learner who wants structured path

## Choose Your Language First (Important!)

Pick **one** language and stick to it for at least 6–9 months.

Recommended for beginners in 2025–2026:

| Language     | Difficulty for Beginners | Job Demand | Best For                  | HackerRank Support |
|--------------|---------------------------|------------|---------------------------|--------------------|
| Python       | ★☆☆ Very Easy            | Very High  | Fast learning, interviews | Excellent         |
| C++          | ★★★ Hard syntax          | High       | Competitive programming   | Excellent         |
| Java         | ★★ Medium                | High       | Enterprise, Android       | Very Good         |
| JavaScript   | ★★ Medium                | Very High  | Web + full-stack          | Good              |

**Recommendation for 95% people**: Start with **Python** → later learn C++ if needed for CP.

## Phase 0: Setup (1–2 days)

1. Create free account → https://www.hackerrank.com  
2. Complete your profile (add skills, college, etc.)  
3. Set default language to Python (or your choice)  
4. Go to **Settings** → Editor → Try "Monaco" or "Vim" mode  
5. Bookmark: Problem Solving section

## Phase 1: Absolute Beginner (0–4 weeks)

Focus: Learn syntax + how to think like a programmer

**Best starting point on HackerRank**:

- **30 Days of Code** → https://www.hackerrank.com/domains/tutorials/30-days-of-code  
  (Best structured beginner course — do it in your chosen language)

- After that → **Problem Solving → Introduction** section

**Topics to master in order**:

1. Input / Output (very important on HackerRank!)
2. Variables & Data Types
3. If-else, conditions
4. Loops (for, while)
5. Basic math operations
6. Strings (upper, lower, split, join)
7. Lists / Arrays basics

**Daily target**: 2–4 easy problems + revise concepts

## Phase 2: Beginner → Comfortable (1–3 months)

**Main section**: Problem Solving → Easy problems

**Important topics & order**:

1. Basic Data Types & Operators
2. Strings (advanced manipulation)
3. Arrays / Lists (1D)
4. Sorting & Searching basics
5. Simple Math & Number Theory
6. Bit Manipulation (easy problems only)
7. Recursion basics (very few problems)

**Milestone**: Solve **150–200 easy** problems  
**Tip**: Read **Discuss** tab after solving (or when stuck > 30 min)

## Phase 3: Intermediate (3–7 months)

**Main sections**:

- Problem Solving → Medium
- Interview Preparation Kit (very important!)
- 30 Days of Code → recap harder days
- Certification Tests (Python/Java/C++/etc.)

**Key topics**:

1. Arrays (2D also)
2. Hashmaps / Dictionaries
3. Two Pointers
4. Sliding Window
5. Stack & Queue
6. Linked List basics
7. Binary Search
8. Greedy Algorithms
9. Basic Dynamic Programming (1D)
10. Basic Graph (BFS/DFS intro)

**Daily target**: 3–5 medium problems  
**Milestone**: Solve **Interview Preparation Kit** completely + 250–350 medium problems

**Take certifications** → they look good on resume/LinkedIn

## Phase 4: Advanced / Interview Ready (7+ months)

**Focus areas**:

- Problem Solving → Hard
- Algorithms domain
- Data Structures domain
- Contests (Weekly + Monthly)
- Company-specific challenges (Google, Amazon folders if available)

**Advanced topics**:

1. Advanced Dynamic Programming (2D, state-based)
2. Graphs (Shortest Path – Dijkstra, Bellman-Ford, Floyd-Warshall)
3. Trees (Binary Tree, BST, Traversals)
4. Heap / Priority Queue
5. Trie
6. Segment Tree / Fenwick Tree (if doing very high level CP)
7. Advanced Bit Manipulation
8. Game Theory basics

**Milestone**:

- Solve 100+ hard problems
- Rank in top 10–20% in contests
- Solve most Interview Preparation Kit + company tagged problems

## General Tips That Actually Work

- **Stuck > 30–45 min?** → Read editorial / discuss (but code yourself!)
- **Revise** old solved problems every 2–3 weeks
- **Make notes** of patterns (two pointers, sliding window, etc.)
- **Don't compare** rank early — focus on understanding
- **Consistency > intensity** — 1–2 hrs daily better than 10 hrs once a week
- **Mock interviews** → use Pramp / Interviewing.io later
- **Track progress** — use spreadsheets or LeetCode-style trackers

## Suggested Weekly Schedule (Intermediate+)

- Mon–Fri: 4–6 new problems (mostly medium/hard)
- Sat: Contest + upsolve
- Sun: Revise weak topics + old problems

